<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beye Addresses Huambo Residents </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beye Addresses Huambo Residents </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB1906113894 Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro in 
Portuguese 0600 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1906113894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] UN Special Representative Alioune Blondin Beye, who 
held a meeting with the National Union for the Total 
Independence of Angola [UNITA] leadership for more than four 
hours in the city of Huambo, addressed the following words to 
Huambo residents: 
  [Begin Beye recording, in French fading into Portuguese 
translation] Dr. Savimbi, chairman of the National Union for the 
Total Independence of Angola [UNITA], and residents of Huambo: 
on behalf of the team accompanying me, ambassadors of the United 
States, Portugal, and the Russian Federation, I thank you for 
welcoming us. We are trying to help solve all the difficulties 
you and all other Angolan populations are facing. We have been 
meeting in Lusaka for seven months now, trying to achieve a 
peaceful solution for the Angolan crisis. Quoting the words of 
Dr. Savimbi, we have already gone 90 percent of the way. 
Following the fruitful talks we held this morning, we believe 
there will be a way out of the current situation in Angola. We 
know that you have no food, that there is war in Angola, and 
that everyone wants peace. If you support your leaders, we 
believe we will soon achieve peace in the country. 
  I thank you very much for your presence here this morning. I 
am aware that you have faced innumerous hardships, you have been 
brave, since you have been keeping us company the whole day. 
Thank you very much. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

