<H3> <TI>   Beye Arrives in Luanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beye Arrives in Luanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB1906074094 London BBC World Service in English 0600 GMT 19 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1906074094 </F>
<F P=104>  London BBC World Service </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "African News" program] </F>
  [Text] The United Nations special representative in Angola, 
Alioune Blondin Beye, is in the capital, Luanda, for talks with 
President Jose Eduardo dos Santos after visiting the UNITA 
[National Union for the Total Independence of Angola] stronghold 
of Huambo yesterday. Speaking on arrival, Mr. Beye said there 
was no deadlock at the peace talks he has been chairing in 
Zambia for the past seven months. He declined to discuss the 
possibility that the UN might withdraw from Angola at the end of 
the month if no settlement was reached. The government and 
UNITA delegations at the talks have returned to consult with 
their leaders in Angola. A government minister, Albino Malungo, 
has appealed to UNITA to allow the resumption of aid flights, 
which were suspended last Monday [13 June], saying food stores 
could otherwise deteriorate. 

</TEXT>

