<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Soldiers Reportedly Take Parts of Kuito </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Soldiers Reportedly Take Parts of Kuito </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB1806061794 Johannesburg SAPA in English 2343 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB1806061794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Luanda June 17 SAPA -- Fighting intensified on 
Friday [17 June] in the Angolan town of Kuito, with government 
forces reportedly gaining control of the southern and western 
parts. State-run radio reported UNITA rebels had deployed two 
commando battalions (about 300 men) to take the town. 
  Government forces this week claimed unidentified aircraft 
had 
dropped supplies for UNITA [National Union for the Total 
Independence of Angola] near Chipeta in the Catabola area. 
  The Angolan News Agency ANGOP said UNITA rebels were also 
trying to capture Malanje town in northern Angola, where heavy 
fighting has killed scores of civilians. 
  Peace negotiators meeting in Zambia are still arguing about 
accommodation for UNITA officials throughout the country if a 
peace settlement is achieved. Reports from Lusaka said UNITA 
wanted the government to provide more than 1,000 houses for its 
officials. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
