<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Cote d'Ivoire </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clarifies Rwanda Mission Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clarifies Rwanda Mission Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1806084994 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 0600 
GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1806084994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] Between 1,000 and 2,000 men 
are needed for the operation in Rwanda, the French foreign 
minister said during his visit to Cote d'Ivoire yesterday. 
Alain Juppe reaffirmed the strict humanitarian character of the 
operation proposed by France. He also insisted that France will 
not and cannot go alone to Rwanda: 
  [Begin Juppe recording] We have said very clearly that our 
intervention should be given the green light by the United 
Nations. We are examining the type of resolution that could give 
a mandate to member states to intervene to save the population, 
which is the prime concern. Several European countries that we 
have contacted have told us, some publicly, that they approve of 
the principle of the operation. I spoke to my Italian, Spanish, 
and British colleagues, and other contacts have been made in 
Paris. Several African countries have also expressed their 
support in principle. 
  We are now examining the concrete modalities of the 
operation, whose duration should be limited; it should have 
precise objectives and should be exclusively humanitarian. The 
aim is to save people who might be wiped out within the next few 
days. It should be carried out by several countries. To avoid 
any ambiguity, France does not wish to go in alone. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

