<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Cote d'Ivoire </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Expresses Support for French Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Expresses Support for French Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB1806161594 Abidjan Radio Cote d'Ivoire Chaine 
Nationale-Une Network in French 1230 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB1806161594 </F>
<F P=104>  Abidjan Radio Cote d'Ivoire Chaine 
Nationale-Une Network </F>

<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] French President Francois Mitterand, in an 
address to a conference held at UNESCO on development, said that 
the sending of humanitarian troops by France to Rwanda is just a 
matter of hours and days. [passage omitted] 
  In a statement to the press this morning, Foreign Minister 
Essy Amara said that our country supported France's initiative. 
  [Begin Amara recording] What is certain is that, at least, 
this initiative has the merit of existing. I think Cote 
d'Ivoire, after all the explanations, fully supports this 
exercise, especially as it does not contravene the resolutions 
adopted in Tunis. The Tunis resolutions underscored the urgent 
need to bring an immediate end to the systematic massacres and 
killings and also called for an immediate end to these heinous 
crimes, which constitute a crime against humanity. I also think 
that another conclusion from Tunis is the urgency in finding a 
solution to these massacres, and it is from this perspective 
that we must consider the French initiative, which consists 
above all in stopping the killings and protecting the people 
assembled in the various camps. As you know, the UN resolution 
-- the UN Observer Mission for Uganda and Rwanda II -- calls for 
the sending of 5,200 troops, but from what we have learned, so 
far, there are only 2,900, which shows the difficulty in 
establishing this force. This is why I believe that in view of 
the urgency of the situation, it is necessary to initiate an ad 
hoc operation. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

