<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Nigeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Announce Handover Date 16 Jan 1995 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government To Announce Handover Date 16 Jan 1995 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB1806185294 Lagos Radio Nigeria Network in English 1800 GMT 
18 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB1806185294 </F>
<F P=104>  Lagos Radio Nigeria Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Federal Government has reaffirmed the specific 
dates for elections at various levels and the terminal date for 
handing over power to a democratically-elected civilian 
government will be announced on 16 January next year. The 
minister of information and culture, Professor Jerry Gana, 
stated this in Abuja yesterday while receiving the new British 
high commissioner to Nigeria, Mr. Thorold Masefield, in his 
office. 
  He said the announcement would mark the commencement of the 
second phase of the political transitional program of the 
present administration. Prof. Gana said government commitment 
to a return to genuine democracy was total and irrevocable. 
  The minister pointed out that the government believed that 
the transitional process should be peaceful, orderly, and 
implemented in accordance with the popular will and not the wish 
of a minority however vocal. Prof. Gana solicited the 
understanding and support of Britain in view of her importance 
in world affairs. 
  Responding, the British high commissioner, Mr. Masefield, 
expressed the hope that the forthcoming national constitutional 
conference would be able to solve the country's political 
problem. He said it was in anticipation of this that he donated 
books recently in support of the conference. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

