<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Nigeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pro-Democracy Students Stage Violent Demonstration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pro-Democracy Students Stage Violent Demonstration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB1906144594 Paris AFP in English 1411 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1906144594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lagos, June 19 (AFP) -- Pro-democracy students in 
western Nigeria Saturday [18 June] staged a violent campus 
demonstration, shattering the windscreen of the state military 
administrator's official car, press reports said here Sunday. 
  About 2,000 students of the Federal University of Technology 
in Akure chanted slogans calling for an immediate end to 
military rule and installation of Chief Moshood Abiola, who 
recently proclaimed himself president and commander-in-chief of 
the armed forces of Nigeria, the reports said. 
  The stone-throwing students barricaded the way to the 
convocation hall and prevented the state military administrator, 
Colonel Mike Torey, from leaving the hall until he addressed 
their demands, the reports said. 
  The students smashed the windscreen of his official car and 
wrote Abiola's name on the sides of the vehicle. 
  Torey, who came to represent President Sani Abacha at a 
convocation ceremony, later addressed the students, promising 
that the government would address the issue of last June's 
annulled presidential election during a constitutional 
conference scheduled to begin June 27 in Abuja. 
  That election, claimed to have been won by Abiola, was 
annulled by the regime of General Ibrahim Babangida for alleged 
irregularities. 

</TEXT>

