<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Senegal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Juppe Praises Diouf for Supporting Rwanda Mission </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Juppe Praises Diouf for Supporting Rwanda Mission </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB1906150094 Paris AFP in French 1213 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1906150094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Dakar, 19 Jun (AFP) -- French Foreign Minister Alain 
Juppe today strongly commended Senegalese President Abdou Diouf 
for having agreed to "involve himself in the French humanitarian 
mission in Rwanda and provide Senegalese soldiers." 
Reiterating "the excellent" nature of Franco-Senegalese 
relations, the French minister, at the end of a 24-hour visit to 
Senegal, added: "Senegal has given the example," hinting that 
other African countries could take part in the French mission, 
which, according to Mr. Juppe, could "take place next week." He 
however refused to specify the number of Senegalese soldiers who 
"will be operating alongside the French soldiers." 
  Authorized sources in Dakar have advanced the figure of 300. 
Senegal has already agreed to provide 800 soldiers for the UN 
Observer Mission for Uganda and Rwanda. During his visit, the 
French foreign minister was received by President Diouf, Prime 
Minister Habib Thiam, and his counterpart Moustapha Niasse. He 
left Dakar late this morning for Paris. 

</TEXT>

