<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Official, Government, UNITA Teams Leave Lusaka </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Official, Government, UNITA Teams Leave Lusaka </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB1806124594 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
1200 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1806124594 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Alves Antonio in Lusaka] </F>
  [Text] Good afternoon! This morning UN Special 
Representative Alioune Blondin Beye left the Zambian capital for 
Huambo and will later leave for Luanda. A source close to the 
mediator told Radio Nacional that Alioune Blondin Beye will take 
this opportunity to hold talks with President of the Republic 
Jose Eduardo dos Santos and Jonas Savimbi, leader of the 
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola [UNITA]. 
The source said the UN official will discuss two issues linked 
to war in Angola: distribution of humanitarian aid and the 
Angolan peace talks underway in Lusaka. 
  The UNITA negotiating team has also left for Huambo and it 
is 
presumed that this trip in within the framework of the usual 
consultations with its leadership at a time when the Lusaka 
talks are apparently at a standstill due to the intransigent 
positions defended by Savimbi's team on the issue regarding the 
installation of UNITA and its senior officials and the retention 
of 76 foreign nationals by UNITA in Huambo, which over the past 
two days has caused intense diplomatic movement. 
  Taking the advantage of the temporary suspension of the 
talks, the government representatives left for Luanda and are 
scheduled to return to Lusaka tomorrow. 

</TEXT>

