<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Liberia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Renews Appeal for ECOMOG Deployment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Renews Appeal for ECOMOG Deployment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB2006131594 Monrovia Radio ELBC in English 0900 GMT 20 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> AB2006131594 </F>
<F P=104>  Monrovia Radio ELBC </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Liberian Peace Council [LPC] is again appealing 
to the West African peacekeeping force, ECOMOG [Economic 
Community of West African States Cease-Fire Monitoring Group], 
to be deployed in areas under the LPC's control. The LPC 
secretary general, Octavius Walker, said the LPC has 
persistently called on ECOMOG to deploy in Rivercess, Sinoe, 
Grand Gedeh, and other areas. He said ECOMOG has refused to do 
so because ECOMOG wants the LPC to declare unilateral cease-fire 
(?even though) it is not a party to the Cotonou Accord. But Mr. 
Walker told LINA [LIBERIA NEWS AGENCY] on Saturday [18 June] 
that he does not understand why ECOMOG cannot take advantage of 
their offer when the peacekeepers responded to a similar offer 
in Tubmanburg, Bomi County, at a time there was fighting in the 
Bomi area. Mr. Walker said since there is no fighting in 
Rivercess, Sinoe, Upper Grand Gedeh, and Grand Bassa Counties, 
ECOMOG should test the willingness of the LPC to cooperate in 
the peace process by deploying peacekeepers in those areas. 
  Meanwhile, the ECOMOG High Command has insisted on the 
cessation of hostilities as a precondition for deployment. 

</TEXT>

