<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Nigeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nadeco Opposes Constitutional Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nadeco Opposes Constitutional Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB2006162094 Paris AFP in English 1557 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2006162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lagos, June 20 (AFP) -- The National Democratic 
Coalition (Nadeco), an amalgam of pro-democracy groups in 
Nigeria, condemned Monday [20 June] a "campaign of 
misinformation" by the military government and stressed its 
opposition to the convening of a national constitutional 
conference. 
  In an official statement here, the Nadeco said that only 
Chief Moshood Abiola could set up "a legitimate Sovereign 
National Conference". 
  On June 11 Abiola, widely perceived as the winner of 
annulled 
elections held a year ago, proclaimed himself "President and 
Commander-In-Chief of the Armed Forces of Nigeria." 
  The statement Monday, signed by Nadeco General Secretary Ayo 
Opadokun, said that the Nigerian people "now have in place the 
president they have freely elected to preside over this nation 
who is now the only morally and legally competent authority to 
administer the affairs of Nigeria." The constitutional 
conference, planned by the government to start in Abuja next 
Monday, "can never produce democracy," the Nadeco added. 
  The insistence of the government to go ahead with the 
conference while two constitutions (1979 and 1989) remained 
unused was a "pointer to its lack of programme except the 
perpetuation of itself in office" and a display of 
"insensitivity" of the military to the wishes of Nigerians. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

