<H3> <TI>   Students Demonstrate Against French Action in Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Students Demonstrate Against French Action in Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA2006211094 Bujumbura Radio-Television Nationale du Burundi 
Radio in French 1800 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA2006211094 </F>
<F P=104>  Bujumbura Radio-Television Nationale du Burundi 
Radio </F>

<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A peaceful demonstration was held in Bujumbura this 
afternoon by Burundi University students. [Name indistinct] 
reports. 
  [Correspondent] The students believed to be [words 
indistinct] thousands, gathered in front of the Burundi 
University dining hall. then they went to the French Embassy in 
Burundi and then to the Novotel Hotel. They passed through 
Unity Boulevard, in front of the [word indistinct] building 
[words indistinct] and ended their march at the Prince Louis 
Rwagasore stadium. Many of the slogans on their placards (?were 
against) Mitterrand and France's policy in Rwanda and Burundi, 
and read as follows: Mitterrand Sacrificed Rwandans; He Is 
Going To Sacrifice Burundians; [words indistinct] of the 
Subregion: Unite; the French African Policy is Meant To Cause 
Harm; France Should Answer for Its Crimes Committed in Africa; 
[words indistinct] Should Remember Vietnam. 
  Other placards called on the Burundi authorities not to 
accept the transit of French troops through Burundi. The 
rejection of French troops was the motive for organizing the 
peaceful demonstration. At the end of their march at Prince 
Louis Rwagasore stadium, the students dispersed after deciding 
to meet tomorrow for a similar march, organized this time by the 
coalition of opposition political parties. In their own words 
[words indistinct] it is a question of combat and, currently, 
demonstrations are the best way to win. 

</TEXT>

