<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peace Negotiations To Resume as Scheduled </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Peace Negotiations To Resume as Scheduled </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2006201394 Luanda TPA Television Network in Portuguese 
1930 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2006201394 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda TPA Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Manuel da Conceicao in Lusaka] </F>
  [Text] After a break in the peace talks at the request of 
the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola [UNITA], 
everything indicates that the negotiating teams will resume 
talks tomorrow. Over the weekend, Alioune Blondin Beye, special 
representative of the UN secretary general in Angola and 
mediator in the peace talks, was in Huambo and Luanda, where he 
held contacts at the highest level. He returned to Lusaka last 
evening. 
  The UNITA negotiating team returned this afternoon from 
Huambo, where it held talks with its leader, Jonas Savimbi, and 
its leadership. The government negotiating team, which used the 
break to go to Luanda, also returned to Lusaka early this 
evening. All the people involved in the peace talks are here in 
Lusaka, but it is still not known what the negotiating teams 
will discuss tomorrow. 
  Before the peace talks were interrupted, the negotiating 
teams from the government and UNITA were discussing the 
involvement of UNITA and its senior leaders in the government. 
  Meanwhile, on the occasion of Africa Refugee Day today, 
Angolan refugees here in Zambia called on the government and 
UNITA to speed up the present talks with a view to establishing 
peace in Angola, because they are tired of living as refugees. 
There are 50,000 Angolan refugees in Zambia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

