<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Rwanda </F>
<H3> <TI>   RPF Continues Stance Against French Intervention </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    RPF Continues Stance Against French Intervention </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Says Neighbors Reject Proposal </H4>

<F P=102> EA2106173994 (Clandestine) Radio Muhabura in French to 
Rwanda 1030 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA2106173994 </F>
<F P=104>  (Clandestine) Radio Muhabura </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] The Rwandan Patriotic Front [RPF] categorically 
rejects and strongly opposes French military intervention 
throughout Rwandan territory. [passage omitted] 
  In addition to the RPF, numerous countries, notably those in 
the Great Lakes region, have also made public their opposition 
to French military intervention in Rwanda. We have spoken, for 
example, of the reaction of Tanzanian Prime Minister John 
Malecela, who condemned the French intervention in Rwanda, 
because the OAU and United Nations are dealing genuinely with 
the Rwandan issue. [passage omitted] 
  The situation is similar in Zaire. The opposition there 
condemned French military intervention in Rwanda, and asked the 
Zairean Government not to back the French, notably by giving 
them a military base. Another neighboring country is Uganda: 
President Yoweri Kaguta Museveni, who is on a visit to the 
United States, has stated that French military intervention in 
Rwanda will be a disaster, as it is opposed by the RPF. 
  It is worth recalling at this juncture that the RPF has made 
this clear, by warning the international community and those 
countries who ally themselves with France. This French 
intervention risks going beyond Rwanda's borders, and might even 
set the whole region ablaze. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

