<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Rwanda </F>
<H3> <TI>   African Observers To Quit Kigali After RPF Threats </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    African Observers To Quit Kigali After RPF Threats </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB2106210594 Paris AFP in English 2049 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2106210594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kigali, June 21 (AFP) -- UN military observers from 
Senegal, Congo and Togo will leave Kigali Wednesday [22 June] 
after receiving threats from Rwandan rebels over France's 
planned military intervention, UN sources said Tuesday. 
  More than 40 out of a total of 124 observers in Rwanda will 
quit the capital city, the sources said. The overall UN mission 
in Rwanda comprises 495 personnel. 
  French-speaking Senegal, Congo and Togo are seen as 
supporting Paris' plan to send 2,000 troops to Rwanda to halt 
ethnic slaughter raging since early April. 
  UN military observers said Rwandan rebels fiercely opposed 
to 
the French intervention plan have agreed to escort the African 
observers to the Ugandan border. 
  The rebels, mainly Tutsis, are wary of France because of its 
past support of President Juvenal Habyarimana, a Hutu whose 
death in an April 6 plane crash touched off the violence. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-24037 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr120_a_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-120 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Rwanda </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ambassador: Government Supports French Initiative </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ambassador: Government Supports French Initiative </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106171794 Brussels La Une Radio Network in French 1600 
GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2106171794 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels La Une Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Violence is still prevailing in Rwanda. [passage 
omitted] 
  As for the Rwandan interim government, which was set up at 
the beginning of the wave of violence in Rwanda, it has just 
taken sides. As was expected, this government has expressed 
support for the French initiative through the Rwandan ambassador 
in Brussels. However, Rwandan Ambassador Francois 
Ngarukiyintwali, first clearly denied that there were French 
troops in the government zone: 
  [Begin Ngarukiyintwali recording] First, I would like to 
recall the allegations made by the Rwandan Patriotic Front [RPF] 
about the alleged presence of French troops in Rwanda. The 
Rwandan Government supports the initiative of the French 
Government in launching humanitarian intervention on the ground 
in Rwanda, with a view to protecting and rescuing people who are 
in a dangerous situation. The Rwandan Government believes that 
this humanitarian and [word indistinct] action should cover both 
the zone controlled by the government and that occupied by the 
RPF. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

