<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   ANC, IFP Agree to Referendum on Natal Capital </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ANC, IFP Agree to Referendum on Natal Capital </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2206053894 Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network in English 1800 
GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2206053894 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The political logjam over KwaZulu/Natal's capital 
has been broken at a marathon session of the province's cabinet 
in Pietermaritzburg. The issue: Should Ulundi be the capital 
or should it be Pietermaritzburg? The cabinet has agreed to 
hold a referendum on the question within 18 months and to set up 
a special commission to determine which city should be the 
interim capital. 
  [Begin recording] [Correspondent Fawzia Moodley] Today's 
agreement comes in the wake of a major public row between the 
IFP [Inkatha Freedom Party], which favors Ulundi, and the ANC, 
which wants Pietermaritzburg as the capital. There appears to 
have been some tough talking during the seven-hour session, but 
KwaZulu/Natal's interests seem to have won in the end. This was 
underlined by an agreement to alternate legislative assembly 
meetings between Pietermaritzburg and Ulundi, while the special 
commission's report is pending. 
  [KwaZulu/Natal Premier Frank Mdlalose] The referendum will 
be 
the one to decide where the capital is going to be. Now for the 
sake of having a referendum naturally we must have a voters' 
roll, which will indicate who are the residents of KwaZulu/Natal. 
  [Moodley] ANC provincial leader Jacob Zuma said a referendum 
was the way forward. 
  [Zuma] The discussions with our colleagues today have made 
all of us to agree to the way forward that we have agreed. 
  [Moodley] The agreement should ease tensions, which reached 
dangerous levels after both IFP leader and Home Affairs Minister 
Mangosuthu Buthelezi, and ANC MP Peter Mokaba entered the debate 
recently. The first sitting of the provincial legislature due 
to have been held in Ulundi next week has been postponed to late 
July or early August. Dr. Mdlalose said bills which were to 
have been debated hadn't yet been drafted. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-24052 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr120_c_94006" </HT>


