<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government, UNITA Teams Fail To Agree on Housing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government, UNITA Teams Fail To Agree on Housing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2206053994 Luanda TPA Television Network in Portuguese 
1900 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2206053994 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda TPA Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Manuel da Conceicao in Lusaka] </F>
  [Text] The whole day today, the government and the National 
Union for the Total Independence of Angola [UNITA] discussed the 
accommodation of UNITA and its senior officials. The UNITA 
negotiating team had been in Huambo last week, where it 
consulted its leadership. However, it has brought nothing new 
to Lusaka, since it is still demanding 1,100 houses. UNITA 
wants houses in good condition and does not want to repair them. 
The government has already told UNITA that it will provide 
houses only for UNITA high officials. It is said that UNITA 
needs only 300 houses, including houses for high officials, who 
number less than 100. The government already has a well defined 
position: Either UNITA accepts what is offered to it within the 
government's capabilities, or nothing will be achieved. Today's 
talks were lengthy and the negotiating teams did not reach any 
agreement. Tomorrow, the negotiating teams will continue 
discussing this issue of housing, in the presence of the 
mediators and observers. 

</TEXT>

