<H3> <TI>   UNITA Radio Reports on Fighting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UNITA Radio Reports on Fighting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2106173894 Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro in 
Portuguese 1200 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2106173894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jamba Voz da Resistencia do Galo Negro </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Italicized passages recorded] </F>
  [Text] Fierce clashes are taking place in N'dalatando, the 
capital of Cuanza Norte Province, where Popular Movement for the 
Liberation of Angola-Labor Party [MPLA-PT] troops tried to link 
N'dalatando to Malanje. 
  Over the past few days the Armed Forces for the Liberation 
of 
Angola [FALA] blocked the warmongering adventure of the Futungo 
de Belas, which with impressive war equipment tried to break the 
FALA defensive lines. FALA's prompt response forced Eduardo dos 
Santos' troops to retreat 25 km following hard clashes in Pamba. 
At present, everything is secure in the city of N'dalatando. 
Our correspondent Felix Miranda reports from Soyo: 
  [Miranda] The situation in N'dalatando deteriorated 
over the past few days when an enormous People's Armed Forces 
for the Liberation of Angola [FAPLA] convoy made up 
of about 105 vehicles, carrying troops and war materiel to 
assist its regiments [words indistinct] with about 15 
armored vehicles. [passage indistinct] 
  The UNITA armed forces over the past few days destroyed a 
war 
helicopter, more than 10 armored vehicles, and captured an 
assortment of military equipment, including 15 troop transports, 
15 radios, and two D-30 guns. 
  Since the Luanda Communist government began intense air and 
ground raids all over the country on 29 May 1994, the residents 
of the plateau city of Bie [Kuito] have never experienced peace. 
Incessant air raids by Eduardo dos Santos' air force have been 
causing numerous victims, particularly in the most vulnerable 
group of the society -- old people, women, and children. The 
situation has grown worse over the past five days. Our 
correspondent Jardo Prata reports: 
  [Prata] Between 16 and 20 June, more than 300 powerful 
bombs were dropped by Sukhoi MiG's [as heard] over Cantifula, 
Fatima, (Quiluto), (Candanga), and (Calumpanga) wards. The two 
last wards are located more than 15 km from the city of Bie. The 
human and material losses are extensive. 
  Meanwhile, Eduardo dos Santos' war aircraft once again 
bombed 
civilian wards and settlements today. 
  [Prata] This morning, Eduardo dos Santos' MiGs once 
again bombed (Tecnicombe) and Popular wards twice. In this 
murderous rampage, at least three people were killed, a 
29-year-old woman carrying her baby and an 18-year-old girl. 

</TEXT>

