<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Congo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Reiterates Support for UN Rwanda Mission </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Reiterates Support for UN Rwanda Mission </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB2206122094 Dakar PANA in English 1048 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2206122094 </F>
<F P=104>  Dakar PANA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Brazzaville, 22 June (PANA) -- The Congolese 
foreign affairs minister, Benjamin Bounkoulou, has reiterated 
his country's support to the creation of the United Nations 
Assistance Mission in Rwanda (UNAMIR II) to save lives and put 
an end to the wanton killings. 
  In a press statement released Tuesday [21 June] in 
Brazzaville, Bounkoulou recalled that Congo was not only 
involved in the OAU military observer mission, but also supports 
the further expansion of the United Nations [words indistinct] 
in that war torn country. 
  Congo has accepted to contribute 300 troops to Rwanda within 
the framework of the proposed UNAMIR. One hundred troops 
already volunteered to go to Rwanda while 200 others will be 
chosen by the government. Already, 25 Congolese troops were 
[words indistinct] the UNAMIR. [passage omitted] 
  Congo is among the 16 African countries asked by the United 
Nations to send 5,500 troops to Rwanda to carry out humanitarian 
assignments and peace-keeping work. 

</TEXT>

