<H3> <TI>   Political Parties, Other Groups React to Keys' Speech </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Political Parties, Other Groups React to Keys' Speech </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    SACOB: Plan To Finance RDP `Sensible' </H4>

<F P=102> MB2306074694 Johannesburg SAPA in English 2357 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2306074694 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Johannesburg June 22 SAPA -- A phased approach to 
financing the government's Reconstruction and Development 
Programme [RDP] was "eminently sensible", the South African 
Chamber of Business [SACOB] said in reaction to the budget on 
Wednesday [22 June]. SACOB welcomed the reduction in the 
standard corporate tax rate, the removal of certain import 
surcharges and the maintaining of the value added tax (VAT) 
rate, saying these would encourage economic growth. 
  "Given the extraordinary increase in expenditure directly 
linked to the transition, the Minister (of Finance Mr Derek 
Keys) has been bold in dealing with the matter directly." 
  SACOB said the appointment of a commission of inquiry into 
taxation avoided immediate tax decisions and prolonged 
uncertainty about a future tax regime. "It is to be regretted 
that the overall effect of the tax changes has been to increase 
the burden on individuals at a time when personal savings are 
still at a low level and the effect of budget creep on 
individuals has not been addressed." 

</TEXT>

