<H3> <TI>   Political Parties, Other Groups React to Keys' Speech </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Political Parties, Other Groups React to Keys' Speech </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Nactu Warns of Possible Conflict </H4>

<F P=102> MB2306074594 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0035 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2306074594 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Johannesburg June 22 SAPA -- The five per cent 
transition levy had the potential to cause conflict between 
workers and the government, the National Council of Trade Unions 
[Nactu] warned on Wednesday [22 June]. Reacting to the 1994/5 
budget announced by Finance Minister Derek Keys, Nactu said it 
believed the levy, its percentage and period should have been 
negotiated. 
  It was "ironic" the minister could tax workers and companies 
the same levy and the lack of consultation was "business as 
usual from the old apartheid regime style of doing things". 
  "We don't even know how the R4 billion [rand] of 
transitional 
costs was incurred," said Nactu Assistant General Secretary 
Mahlomola Skhosana. 
  Nactu had always stood for a negotiated levy towards 
specific 
programmes such as education and training in the Reconstruction 
and Development Programme. The R2.5 billion kick-start to the 
programme was a "drop in the ocean compared to the general needs 
of people", said Mr Skhosana. 
  Nactu was also concerned the government would settle the R15 
billion debt incurred by the former TVBC [Transkei, 
Bophuthatswana, Venda, Ciskei] states instead of investing it in 
the development programme, the statement said. 
  Nactu welcomed the establishment of a tax commission, saying 
it was long overdue. "We hope the commission will act with 
integrity and consult every stakeholder and all trade union 
national centres, instead of some and not others." 

</TEXT>

