<H4>    CP Objects to Income Tax Levy </H4>

<F P=102> MB2306074394 Johannesburg SAPA in English 2330 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2306074394 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pretoria June 22 SAPA -- The Conservative Party [CP] 
on Wednesday [22 June] strongly objected to the five per cent 
levy on income tax imposed on "already overtaxed taxpayers". 
  "The CP strongly objects to the squandering of R4 billion 
[rand] by the Transitional Executive Council and the Independent 
Electoral Commission," the party's finance spokesman Cas Uys 
said in a statement. He said the amount now had to be made up 
for through a five per cent levy. 
  Mr Uys said the insufficient increase in social, military 
and 
civil pensions resulted in a further lowering of living 
standards in a sector of the community which, in some cases, was 
already below the breadline. "The budgeted shortage in the 
current financial year of R29.3 billion will once more result in 
a drastic increase in government debt," he said. 
  He said if the government did not succeed in bringing about 
law and order and stability there would be no influx of capital 
to South Africa and its entrance to international markets would 
fail. 

</TEXT>

