<H3> <TI>   Political Parties, Other Groups React to Keys' Speech </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Political Parties, Other Groups React to Keys' Speech </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    DP: Budget Aimed at `Soft Targets' </H4>

<F P=102> MB2306075494 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0045 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2306075494 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cape Town June 22 SAPA -- Minister of Finance Mr 
Derek Keys unfortunately went primarily for soft targets in 
Wednesday's [22 June] budget, said Democratic Party [DP] finance 
spokesman Ken Andrew. He said in a statement middle-income 
taxpayers would be hardest hit. Individual taxes were up 18.4 
per cent and had more than doubled in the past five years. 
  The R6.5 billion [rand] additional revenue from taxes on 
individuals' incomes was "the highest ever". 
  The government was still living beyond its means. Continued 
budget deficits were mortgaging South Africa's future and 
pushing it ever closer to the debt trap that had financially 
ruined many developing countries. 
  Mr Andrew said the government should have cut defence 
spending, not increased it by 13 per cent. In contrast, spending 
on police was up by only 6.5 per cent, less than the inflation 
rate, at a time when crime was rampant. This made no sense. 
  The DP was not opposed in principle to the one-off levy to 
finance South Africa's transition to democracy but was alarmed 
by the enormous cost of the transition. The party would question 
whether the money had been properly spent and adequately 
controlled. 

</TEXT>

