<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Political Parties, Other Groups React to Keys' Speech </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    FF Critical of Impact on Taxpayer </H4>

<F P=102> MB2306081594 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0153 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2306081594 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pretoria June 22 SAPA -- The poor and defenceless 
individual taxpayer, who already carried most of the tax burden, 
would have to cough up yet again, the Freedom Front [FF] said on 
Wednesday in its reaction to the budget. FF financial spokesman 
Dr Willie Botha said most of the transition expenditures which 
the taxpayer had to foot had been been unnecessary. 
  The failed National Peacekeeping Force had cost the taxpayer 
R395 million [rand] and the Independent Electoral Commission had 
overshot its budget by R700 million. 
  Dr Botha added that the measures envisaged to stimulate 
growth would have a negligible impact on job creation. The 
danger existed that those who qualified for these benefits would 
benefit themselves, rather than create jobs. 
  He said it was difficult to imagine how economic growth 
alone 
would meet the increasing demands of the Reconstruction and 
Development Programme. 
  According to Dr Botha foreign investment would probably only 
be realised after the first real african national congress 
budget in 1995, provided the ANC indicated its support for a 
free market economy. 

</TEXT>

