<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Political Parties, Other Groups React to Keys' Speech </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Economist Calls Budget `Laudable Attempt' </H4>

<F P=102> MB2306083094 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0155 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2306083094 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Johannesburg June 22 SAPA -- This year's budget is 
"a laudable attempt" to deal with problems head-on and build on 
sound fiscal growth, but financial discipline will determine if 
the shocks have only been delayed until next year, Syfrets 
[financial institution] economist Elmien de Kock said in a 
statement on Wednesday. [22 June] 
  "It is not a redistribution budget; it's a reconstruction 
budget," she said. 
  "It is only by increasing the economic pie that the 
underprivileged can benefit from wealth redistribution...The 
only way the government can sustain an increase in revenue is by 
growing the tax base." 
  The one-off five per cent levy to finance the country's 
transition to democracy would hurt high-income individuals 
without curbing consumer spending because most breadwinners were 
not affected. 
  The deficit before borrowing of R29.6 billion [rand] was not 
onerous because it included transition costs of R4 billion. 
  Mrs de Kock said Syfrets expected a negative reaction 
initially from capital markets but there was potential for lower 
bond yields. 
  The financial rand would not be abolished in the next six 
months, she said. 
  The corporate tax rate cut would offset the transition levy. 
Companies with low dividend cover would most likely be adversely 
affected, while those with average cover would lose about four 
per cent in earnings per share. 
  Beer and tobacco tax rises would not substantially affect 
sales volumes. 
  The construction sector had reacted positively to pre-budget 
announcements on job creation and public works programmes, Mrs 
de Kock said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

