<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meiring Warns of Declining Defense Capabilities </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meiring Warns of Declining Defense Capabilities </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2306055494 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1857 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2306055494 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Parliament June 22 SAPA -- Serious shortcomings had 
developed in both the combat and logistical support capabilities 
of the South African National Defence Force [SANDF] because of 
cutbacks in defence spending, the SANDF said on Wednesday [22 
June]. A document released by the chief of the SANDF, Gen Georg 
Meiring, said the defence budget would have to increase in 
future years. 
  The defence allocation had declined by 44 percent in real 
terms during the past five years and was now equivalent to the 
defence budget of the mid-1970s. Capital spending on armaments 
and equipment had dropped from 44 percent of the overall defence 
budget in 1989 to 28 percent last year and the SANDF could no 
longer maintain even minimum strategic technological levels. 
  "The annual reductions in the defence budget not only 
necessesitated a reduction in the diversity of capabilities 
available within the SANDF, but also caused a drastic reduction 
in the quality and depth of combat capability." 
  Gen Meiring said the costs of integrating non-statutory 
forces such Umkhonto We Sizwe [Spear of the Nation, ANC armed 
wing] into the SANDF would increase defence spending in the 
short term, as would the costs of retrenchments resulting from 
such rationalisation. 
  Although defence laid claim to a large proportion of state 
revenue, it also contributed to the national economy through 
production, employment and foreign exchange earnings. He said 
the export of armaments and related equipment had earned South 
Africa R750 million [rands] in foreign exchange between April 
1993 and January 1994. 
  While the conventional threat at present was low, South 
Africa had to maintain all its existing combat capabilities. 
Moderate, expandable force levels were needed to enable the 
SANDF to gear up to war force levels if and when needed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-24078 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr121_c_94013" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-121 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Armed Forces To Establish Command in Port Elizabeth </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Armed Forces To Establish Command in Port Elizabeth </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2306055794 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1437 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2306055794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Port Elizabeth June 22 SAPA -- The new Eastern 
Province [EP] Command -- incorporating the old SA [South 
African] Defence Force and the armies of two liberation 
movements and two former homelands -- will be based in Port 
Elizabeth. EP command will comprise the African National 
Congress' Umkhonto We Sizwe [Spear of the Nation], Pan 
Africanist Congress' Azanian Peoples Liberation Army and the 
former Ciskei and Transkei Defence Forces. 
  The structure of the integrated force was outlined by Lt-Col 
J M Swanepoel at a media briefing on Tuesday [21 June] night. 
He said it had been decided early in the planning of 
integration that the new EP Command would cover the former 
Eastern Province and Border/Kei areas. 

  -  EP Command would be divided into five army districts: 
  -  Hantam Army District with its headquarters in Grahamstown; 
  -  Algoa Army District with headquarters in Port Elizabeth; 
  -  Border/Kei Army District with headquarters in East London; 
  -  East-Border Army District with headquarters in Queenstown; 
and 
  -  Transkei Army District with its headquarters in Umtata. 


    EP Command commanding officer Brig Toon Slabbert said the 
SANDF aimed to establish a strong core army, whose primary role 
would be defence. 
  Secondary roles would be to preserve life and the health of 
the population; to assist the police in maintaining order; to 
provide essential services, especially in disaster areas; and to 
support the nation's socio-economic upliftment. 
  The SANDF [South African National Defense Force] would use 
the former SADF as the core around which to develop a strong 
apolitical force with high standards and full-time and part-time 
components. 
  Brig Slabbert said with the integration of the SADF, former 
TVBC [Transkei, Bophuthatswana, Venda, and Ciskei] armies and 
non-statutory forces, the SANDF could comprise about 130,000 
soldiers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

