<H4>    Abiola Addresses Supporters </H4>

<F P=102> AB2206153394 Paris AFP in English 1516 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2206153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lagos, 22 Jun (AFP) -- Nigerian opposition leader 
Moshood Abiola, sought by security forces since June 11, on 
Wednesday defied the military regime by making a public address 
to more than 2,000 people in the heart of the capital. Abiola 
supporters went wild when the Muslim millionaire tycoon, missing 
since he slipped away under the nose of police earlier this 
month while under house arrest, suddenly surfaced in Lagos. He 
proclaimed himself president and Armed Forces commander-in-chief 
on June 11, saying he was the legitimate winner of the June 12, 
1993, presidential elections later cancelled by the military 
authorities. 

</TEXT>

