<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Rwanda </F>
<H3> <TI>   RPF Reiterates Opposition to French Intervention </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    RPF Reiterates Opposition to French Intervention </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706143094 Paris Radio France International in French 1230 
GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2706143094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio France International </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe said this 
morning that the rebels' opposition to French intervention is 
dying down. Monique Mas has just spoken to Major Emmanuel 
Ndahiro, military spokesman of the RPF [Rwandan Patriotic 
Front], and asked him if the RPF has softened its stand: 
  [Begin Ndahiro recording, in English fading into French 
translation] Not at all. We have not changed our position 
toward the French intervention. Considering past French 
actions, we are still opposing it. They were responsible for 
the killings in Rwanda and we have no reason whatsoever to trust 
them. As you know, they have never helped solve our problems. 
We could not prevent them from coming here. What RPF leaders 
say is that if the French limit their intervention to the 
Zairean border and to humanitarian actions we will not clash 
with them. We issue a warning to the French: History has taught 
us that they have not come to rescue 8,000 people, but to 
protect the criminals who have murdered more than 500,000 
people. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

