<F P=100> EAST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Kenya </F>
<H3> <TI>   Low Turnout Reported at Polling Stations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Low Turnout Reported at Polling Stations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA2706192394 Nairobi KTN Television Network in English 1000 
GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA2706192394 </F>
<F P=104>  Nairobi KTN Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Low turnout characterized early morning voting in 
almost all the polling stations in Kakamega's [western Kenya] 
three constituencies, where by-elections are taking place today. 
  An early morning survey by KTN in Lurambi, Ikolomani, and 
Shinyalu constituencies revealed that all the polling stations 
opened at 0600. By 1000 very few stations had registered more 
than 20 voters. The three constituencies have between 20,000 to 
30,000 registered voters. Throughout the constituencies, people 
went about their normal activities as if they were not aware of 
the by-elections taking place. However, KTN noted some 
encouraging turnouts in a few polling stations, particularly in 
Ikolomani constituency followed by a few polling stations in 
Kakamega town which is largely in Lurambi constituency. Most of 
the voters seen were women and youth who came trickling in small 
groups or singly. 
  KANU [Kenyan African National Union] and FORD [Forum for the 
Restoration of Democracy]-Kenya officials who had been on an 
early morning roundup of the polling stations in the three 
constituencies told KTN that they were satisfied with the 
polling arrangements except for a few anomalies which they had 
detected in some polling stations. In Kakamega town's 
industrial area, the town's mayor, (Morgan Magaga), alleged that 
FORD-Kenya youth were intimidating voters, asking them to vote 
for their party. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

